Comment: I actually really like it, but there are a few things that bother me, or that I think could have been better. The deviant in particular could have been a much more interesting character, considering he has the memories of both Gilgamesh and Ajax, so he knows the eternals didn't know, the Celestials are to blame, and that they are trying to stop the emergence. It would have been so interesting to keep him alive, seeing he has the millions of years of memories of Ajax. Now with Thena, she suddenly controls the mad weary, when again, it would have been really interesting to see a conversation where the eternals tell Mad Weary Thena that they know, and are trying to fix it. Or the fact that none of them ever questioned why Sprite never aged, they could've at least told us why they thought she didn't. Or why Druig just comes back completely unharmed after Ikaris said he killed him, and the fact he could've just put Ikaris to sleep, like we know he did to Thena. Or how Phastos seems to have always hated Ikaris, but it was never shown before, or how they couldn't beat Ikaris together, but then he suddenly can alone, like, idk, tell us he realized he could use the sphere technology to drain his energy, done. I still really like the movie, the acting, the aesthetic, the pacing, I think it's a good movie, but it could've been so much better with a few changes. Plus, this trailer ruined the Ikaris twist, but that's more a complaint for the marketing guys.

Comment:
"Unfortunately, the Eternals movie was not consistent with the Eternals storyline in the comics. There were several differences between the movie and the source material, particularly with respect to the lore and characters. For example, the character Kingo was portrayed as a Bollywood actor in the movie, whereas in the comics, he was a fierce Samurai Eternal. Additionally, the Deviants, an evolutionary offshoot of humanity produced by the Celestials, were depicted differently in the movies compared to their appearance in the comics.

Overall, while the movie was entertaining, it deviated from the established lore and characters of the Eternals in significant ways, leaving fans of the comics disappointed with the inconsistencies."

Comment:
The Eternals is the MCU's answer to DC's Watchmen comic....forever a misunderstood film that may not speak to the current MCU demographic, but brilliant in it's themes and message nonetheless. It may in truth, could have been a good tv show too, but I understand Marvel's trepidation after the lackluster reception of the Inhumans.

I get it. Superman can be the ultimate Objectivist hero --- a concept currently embodied by Batman and Rorschach -- and I understand why we always gravitate towards them. Time and again, movies show the flaws in that concept but we still like them, which goes to show how important it is to incorporate that concept in superhero films.

Comment:
Initially I really just wanted to give this a try when I saw Richard Madden and Kit Harrington being announced. The cast was great, and given so many characters, there was a high chance for most of them to be presented in a shallow way. But I think it was not quite bad, we got to tap into everyone's particularities, even if for just a bit for some. 
For me, mostly when I watch a movie of tv show, most enjoyable thing is when I get lots of wide shots of the scenery, or scenery presented is quite diverse (not just the interior of a building, or camera focusing too much on a character so that you feel like that character is so close, it might take some of your personal place). So, I quite liked that, the diverse scenery.
There was some annoying stuff, and I braced myself to face the comic-book-american-style movie which means lots of... blasphemy and non-sense. (And I also hate the over-the-top political correctness, seriously. What? Complain, if you wanna complain.)
But imagination-wise, I think the story did a decent job.
I enjoyed it more than it annoyed me, I suppose. 
Visually good, cast was good.

Comment:
Now, I'm going to be really honest. This movie sucks. Hear me out first.

Eternals has a good potential, but Marvel made a mistake here, they shouldn't rushed everything into a one movie, the story was messy and scattered and it felt rush, instead of having flashbacks they should have made a series in order to properly introduce the characters.

There were too many characters that as the movie goes on it lost it's ark. Each character was very interesting, but you can't introduce them directly into two hours, as the movie goes on it gets messier, the Celestial that was about to be born didn't seem that threatening. Why? 

Well for me, we didn't have enough background and information about that Celestial, all we know is that once it's born it'll destroy a planet and make the same cycle again, and there were the deviants, the movie had a zig zag feeling where you don't know who you should really focus on, I've been a MCU fan since the x-men era (although x-men is still not part of the MCU, but hoping to happen that soon) and I know not every Marvel movie is good but at least when Marvel shows us a new movie it feels fresh.

And I also agree about Ikaris being the bad guy twist was a rush and made things more confusing and messy, Eternals has a good potential, I hope Marvel will learn it's lesson.
